The paper deals with approximation algorithms for two classic optimization problems in computer science, the Steiner tree problem and the traveling salesman problem (TSP), in the context of both universal and differentially private algorithms. This suggests that the paper could belong to several sub-categories, including cs.DS (data structures and algorithms), cs.IT (information theory), cs.LG (machine learning), cs.CC (computational complexity), and cs.CG (computational geometry). However, given the focus on approximation algorithms and lower bounds, cs.DS and cs.CC seem to be the most likely sub-categories, followed by cs.IT and cs.LG, while cs.CG is less likely but still possible given the geometric nature of the problems.
